title: For Sale:  MOLOT VEPR .308 Winchester Hunting Carbine - 16.5in bbl
postcontent:
For sale is my lightly used, .308/7.62NATO VEPR, seldom shot, kept clean with diesel fuel and CLR. Has maybe 500 rounds through it, only modifications are a cut safety (to lock bolt open for inspection, etc) and screwholes in the forend from a previous rail mounted bipod. 

This one is of the old-school slantback stock variety, much more sought after now that the straightbacks are being imported. This specifically was imported through Arsenal in LV, Nevada, which is the best importer in the US as any AK enthusiast is well aware. This is not a subpar Robarms variant, this is the real thing. 

I paid 1199 for it, only looking for 1000 back, a new safety and forend can be had for under 80 total so if you want it like new, take 80 off the price. I just got a German automobile which requires more TLC than my budget allows, thus, I need to sell this. 

Ohio CCW holders preferred, will accept Ohio DL with stipulation that I run a background check beforehand.  Would much rather the CCW do that for me though. 

Give me your best offer, but NO LOWBALLS. I've had people at ranges beg me to buy this for 1000, don't cut several points off of that and expect a response. That being said, never hurts to try though. 

Comes in original box, with cleaning kit and rod, as well as original manual. Will include my last 20 rounds of 7.62, the original 10rd magazine, and the knock-off Harris bipod as well as a Weaver 4x duplex  scope on a UTG mount (my brothers crap) to whoever gives me the best offer.

Would prefer to meet in Columbus, will travel within reason for a good offer. 

Trust me, for a grand, this is a steal. I've shot sub MOA groups with a 4x weaver on a crap mount. Cant imagine what it would do with a proper optic and TWS rail system. 

Thanks for looking, let me know if interested.

title: For Sale:  Steyr Match Pistol  (FP .22lr)
postcontent:
Steyr Match free pistol.  

Accuracy equal to the average Anschutz target rifle, and better than almost any USA target rifle to 50 Meters.  The only pistol with the barrel at the level of the index finger, to prevent gun rotation while the bullet travels down the barrel.  Probably the most accurate handgun ever made.  The sights are designed to allow the gun to be held canted as well as vertical.  The high sight position does require somewhat different aiming technique that most FPs.  

Use with any velocity ammunition is possible due to the muzzle brake and chamber strength.  10" barrel.  Two weights included.  The weight bar serves to aid in sight alignment and keeping the gun vertical while aiming, and to set up countervibration to increase accuracy.  It also can be used to adjust the feel of the gun.

Left hand standard (large) grip, or rightr hand very large (really very large) grip available, your choice.  Includes OEM plastic case, and instruction manuals (one in English if needed, and original German with test target).

Not a concealable gun, but for transfer purposes, sold as if it were a concealable handgun.  All relevant state and federal laws are followed for transfer, in that regard, including waiting period for a handgun.  Generally legal in CA, but classified as an assault weapon in some of local or state laws.

More images or info on request.  

In the old High Standard terminology, this gun is a 100 XXX.  A thousand of these guns were made.  All were assembled, start to finish, by one person who currently is the director of technical services at Steyr.  Spare parts are available, but only from Steyr Austria.

title: Want To Buy:  1911 .45
postcontent:
I am seeking to purchase a (hopefully mil-spec) full-size 1911 .45 manufactured by a long-time quality brand in the industry.  I'm sure that as you read here, I've already clued you in that I really know absolutely nothing about what's out there these days; the cheap copies over "real deals," etc.  Back some 40 years ago, saying that you're wanting to purchase a 1911 .45 seemed like a simple thing. These days, the variety appears endless; hence, my ignorance.

I know that Colt initially manufactured the gun for the military.  Now, I see a virtual sea of variety that I cannot say exactly what I'm really looking for except to say that I'm seeking as close to what I once knew some 40 years ago.  I hear that Kimber, Colt and Sig Saur are pretty much up there for well-made, quality 1911s, but that's about it.  So, I guess this is where you come in.  I'm certainly open to education...and all reasonable offers to sell to me.

Only OREGON PRIVATE PARTY sellers need reply to this post.  Of course, I'm willing to travel for the right piece and price.  I'd like to keep my outlay to between $500 - $1,000.

You may reach me at REDACTED and/or REDACTED.  

Thanks!

title: For Sale/Trade:  Custom Mauser 25-06 3800fps
postcontent:
For sale or trade. Custom German Mauser in 25-06. Great coyote gun. Has a 1-12" twist barrel. Only shoots light bullets well. My load is a 75gr vmax at a chrono 3800fps. Look up the ballistics on this. It shoots as flat as a 22-250 but hits harder. It also comes with 48 RDS of this load and the reloading data. It will also come with app 100 75gr bullets. The scope is a BSA 8x33x44. I am keeping the bipod the ballistics on this sighted in at 300 yards its 2.3" high at 100 yrds, 3.0" at 200 yards, 7.8' low at 400yds.

Update I shot this rifle today. I shot a little under a 1" group at 100 yards in the terrible wind today. 20mph plus. There was also very little barrel cooling time between shots. Now 42 rds of ammo will come with rifle. 48 -5shot group and 1 fouling shot. In the pic the the shot on the right is from a different rifle.

title: For Sale:  US Army Multicam IOTV Vest (no plates) (BRAND NEW!) (Neck Guards & front and back guards, INCLUDED)
postcontent:
I have a brand new MEDIUM Multicam Improved Outer Tactical Vest, US Army Issue. These are brand new and never worn or seen combat. The vest inlcudes all of the soft armor, kidney pad & collar armor. These sell new for over $1000 if you can find them. 

Please email me and I will get back to you within 10 minutes. Thanks!.. REDACTED


The IOTV is designed to take the weight of the vest off the shoulders and move it to the lower torso. The vest is also equipped with a mesh inner cover that is designed to improve airflow inside of the armor. There is also a back pad in the lower back area of the vest, which is designed to defeat fragmentation impacts to the lower back/kidney areas. However, the back pad does not provide ballistic protection. The vest can withstand a direct impact from a 7.62 millimeter (both NATO and ex-Soviet types) on the front or rear plates (SAPI NIJ standard III), however, the new E-SAPI plates will increase protection to armor-piercing rounds (NIJ standard IV). The IOTV provides, without the ballistic ceramic plates inserted, protection from small caliber rounds (i.e. 9mm) and fragmentation. The soft kevlar panels have been tested to stop 9 mm 124 grain full metal jacket bullets at 1,400 ft/s (426 m/s) with minimal deformation and has a V-50 of roughly 1,525 ft/s (465 m/s). This means that the bullet has to be traveling faster than 1,525 ft/s for it to have more than a 50% chance of breaking through the soft armor panel. These specifications are similar to the NIJ standard level III-A certification, however, military standards do not require their vests to be NIJ certified. This is a huge improvement over the PASGT vest, and the Vietnam era fragmentation vest (which was made of nylon). Both only offered protection against fragmentation

title: For Sale/Trade:  1942 Walther P38 WWII German Nazi Bring-Back Handgun - Marked AC42
location: Santa Barbara to Los Angeles, California, United States
postcontent:
I'm selling my 1942 Walther p38 world war 2 bring-back.

There are NO import markings on this pistol. This is not a russian capture, nor an armory rebuild. This is a mixed serial numbers shooter that was nickel plated by the US GI who brought it back, as was common to do with many bring-back firearms in World War 2. 

There are Waffenamt Stamps (Nazi Eagle markings) all over this pistol, both 359 and 135. the barrel and locking lug are marked with Waffenamt 135, and the frame is marked in 359. The Slide is marked 4202P, as is the barrel.

I am selling this firearm along with the ORIGINAL WWII nickel plated magazine + 4 newer, post war magazines. The Magazines for this firearm hold 8 rounds. Three of them are made by walther post-war, and the fourth is a 10-rd magazine made by a modern manufacturer. The fourth mag is still new in box.  

i originally bought this to add to my collection of world war 2 firearms, but I've decided to sell a few pieces to free up cash for my upcoming wedding.

this firearm is in great shooting condition! It is safe to shoot, all parts were checked and inspected by an expert.  The rifling in the barrel is in FANTASTIC condition, considering the age of the gun is about 71 years old.

This is a C&R so it can be transferred in the State of California through a FFL. If you live out of state, I will have to ship this firearm to your FFL.

This is a fantastic deal. Magazines for this gun are hard to come by, and can go for $90 alone. And you're getting five of them plus the gun.  I will include the hard case in the deal as well.

So I just bought *another* S&W .357. . . and I'm tossing up a mint safe queen to "justify" it. 

Older production S&W model 65-2. Pinned barrel, recessed cylinder. Locks up tighter than any S&W revolver I have ever owned. Crane gap & forcing cone perfect. Heavy barrel model, with serrated combat trigger. Faint turn line. Sweet trigger both SA and DA. Got it years back from an older gent who bought it new -- said he put less than one box of ammo through it -- all .38 spec. Normally I think stories like that are BS, but I believe it on this one. 

Wearing the original number-matching walnut grips. Comes with original S&W box and paperwork, including the oil paper. 

This is likely the closest you're going to get a new pinned and recessed .357 magnum K-frame. 

Feel free to email me with offers. I can send better pics to your email address. Looking to do an in-person transaction w/ an Oregon resident. Thanks!

Re: the m65 -- it is considered by many the ultimate "fighting" K-frame -- to quote a wiser man than me: "the m65 has everything you need, and nothing you don't." No fancy sights to snag your draw, no shrouded ejector rod to slow your reload -- the essential duty weapon from back when the K-frame was the standard sidearm of american law enforcement, made the way they used to make 'em.

title: For Sale:  Vz 24
postcontent:
The vz. 24 rifle[3] is a bolt-action carbine designed and produced in Czechoslovakia from 1924 to 1942. It was developed from the famous Mauser Gewehr 98 line, and features a very similar bolt design. The rifle was designed in Czechoslovakia shortly after World War I, featuring a 600 mm (23.6") barrel which was shorter and considered more handy than the 150 mm (5.9") -longer Gewehr 98. The carbine followed a similar trend in weapon design at the time, that a short rifle gave away little in ballistic efficiency at combat ranges, but was easier to handle on account of its shorter length.

During World War II, the vz. 24 was produced for the German armed forces during its occupation. The rifle was also produced in nearby Slovakia, a German ally and puppet state during the war.

The vz. 24 rifle was widely exported and enjoyed usage during and after World War 2, noticeably by Romania, Iran, Guatemala, China and others. Many of the contract rifles made for South American countries were chambered in 7mm Mauser or 7.65×53mm Argentine.

My rifle was acquired just under a year ago, It is a blast to shoot great rifle I hate to sell it but its the season for heating bills and Christmas and I have recently been laid off.
